  ---
  Silk Hand — Q01 (Easiest)

  Personality: The most "human" of the four — they're criminals running a business. They'd rather take your money than your life.    
  Bribery is the signature gimmick: they're the only faction in the entire game that can actually be bribed, including patrol ships  
  (which can't be bribed at all).

  Combat shape: Significantly weaker stats across the board (×0.85 hull/shields, ×0.80 damage). Slightly more accurate than baseline.
   The lowest negotiation resistance in the game (0.7) means even modest negotiation skill talks them out of fights. They flee 10%   
  more often than baseline.

  Why they work as the starter faction: Q01 contains the player's spawn region (Q01-R0101) and the tutorial. New players who haven't 
  built combat skill yet can survive almost any Silk Hand encounter by paying their way out. The faction teaches the player that     
  combat isn't always required — a critical lesson before they wander into Q03 or Q04.

  Generator content angle: Sophisticated criminals with personality. Names should feel like aliases and noms de guerre. Hideouts are 
  dens, parlors, gambling houses — not fortresses. Black market contacts are smooth talkers, not thugs. Lore should lean into "we're 
  businessmen, not animals." Their warlord should be cunning rather than physically imposing.

  ---
  Phantom Circuit — Q02 (Easy–Medium)

  Personality: Tech-focused ghosts. They'd rather not fight at all — they trade information to escape. Their gimmick is intel as     
  currency: defeating one (or talking your way past one) yields system addresses, blueprints, and rumors that other factions don't   
  drop.

  Combat shape: Roughly average stats but two extreme outliers: ×1.20 accuracy (the highest in the game) and ×1.30 flee chance (the  
  highest as well). They hit hard when they shoot, but they prefer to disengage. Negotiation resist is baseline 1.0 — they'll talk,  
  but they aren't pushovers like Silk Hand.

  Why they work as a step-up: Phantom Circuit teaches the player about evasion as a threat model. You can't easily intimidate them   
  into staying for a fight — they ghost. But you also can't bribe them as cheaply as Silk Hand. The player has to start thinking     
  about positioning and what they actually want from an encounter (loot? intel? clear the system?).

  Generator content angle: Cyber-mystic, hacker-collective vibe. Names that feel like callsigns and handles ("The Cipher," "Nexus"). 
  Hideouts are listening posts, signal arrays, decommissioned observatories. Black market contacts deal in data, blueprints, and     
  cartography. Their warlord should feel like a mastermind in the shadows — never directly seen until the boss fight.

  ---
  Rust Collective — Q03 (Medium–Hard)

  Personality: Industrial scavengers — they want your ship more than your life. Their gimmick is part stripping: a successful Rust   
  Collective attack can permanently remove installed components from the player's ship. Mechanically this represents boarding without
   needing a boarding sub-system. (See 05b_enemies_and_factions.md line 61.)

  Combat shape: The tank of the four — ×1.30 hull and ×1.20 shields, the highest of any faction. They trade accuracy (×0.85) for     
  staying power. Flee chance is zero — they will not retreat. Negotiation resist is 1.4 (high), and they cannot be intimidated. They 
  can be negotiated with, but it's hard, and what they want is your cargo or your parts — so the negotiation outcome is itself       
  painful.

  Why they're the difficulty wall: Rust Collective is the first faction the player can't easily out-talk or out-run. Bribery doesn't 
  work cheap, intimidation is off the table, fleeing them just delays the fight. The player has to actually be combat-ready before   
  pushing into Q03. This is also the first faction whose defeat conditions threaten persistent harm — losing a tier-3 component is a 
  real setback even if you survive.

  Generator content angle: Heavy-industrial, junkyard-warlord aesthetic. Names that feel mechanical, brutalist ("Iron-Marshal Drog," 
  "Foreman of the Pit"). Hideouts are scrapyards, derelict refineries, dismembered station hulks. Black market contacts trade in ship
   parts and salvage. Their warlord should feel like the king of a metal mountain — physically imposing, slow, immovable.

  ---
  Void Reavers — Q04 (Hardest)

  Personality: Nihilistic killers. They don't want your money, your ship, or your information — they want to end you. Negotiation    
  resist 99.0 is not a typo: it's effectively infinite, and can_negotiate: false and can_intimidate: false confirm there is no social
   way out of a Void Reavers encounter. You fight or you die.

  Combat shape: ×1.30 damage — the highest in the game — combined with above-average hull (×1.10) and accuracy (×1.05). Slightly     
  weaker shields (×0.90) is their only soft spot. Zero flee chance. Every fight is to the death.

  Why they're the endgame: By the time the player has the jump-drive tier and combat skill to survive Q04, they should be near peak  
  progression. Void Reavers are a pure DPS race — kill them before they kill you, with no off-ramps. Their warlord is the hardest    
  fight in the game.

  Generator content angle: Cult of personality, death-worship, blood-and-void aesthetic. Names that feel ritualistic and titled      
  ("Captain Vex the Merciless," "Bloodfist of the Void"). Hideouts are charnel houses, voidshrines, broken cathedral-stations. Black 
  market contacts barely qualify as contacts — they're more like wardens deciding whether to let you live. Their warlord should have 
  a title and a creed, not just a name. Lore should hint at why they exist at all — what broke them, why they kill — and leave most  
  of it unanswered.

  ---
  Cross-Faction Mechanics Worth Knowing

  These shape what good content variants look like:

  - Border blending (within 2 regions of a quadrant border): 75/25 → 50/50 → 25/75 mix between adjacent factions. This means a region
   near the Q01/Q02 border has both Silk Hand and Phantom Circuit content. Generator shouldn't write variants assuming a faction is  
  alone in its region.
  - Turf war encounters in border regions can be passive (loot from a recent battle, both factions' goods recoverable) or active (an 
  ongoing fight you can intervene in). Loot variants tied to border regions can lean into this.
  - Fame scaling (enemy_fame = base_fame + floor(distance / 2.5), capped at 10) means the same faction gets stronger as you move     
  outward. A Silk Hand encounter at distance 2 is fame 1; the same encounter at distance 16 is fame 7. So the faction identity stays 
  constant, but variants should still cover the full distance range — generator should produce easy and hard variants for every      
  faction.
  - Loot identity is real. The loot_table for a faction's encounters should reflect their loot focus. Silk Hand drops contraband and 
  shards; Phantom Circuit drops cartography data and blueprints; Rust Collective drops ship components and salvage; Void Reavers     
  drops weapons and raw shards. The generator should reject Void Reavers variants whose loot tables are full of intel or blueprints. 

  ---
  Design Quality Notes

  What works well: The four factions form a clean removal-of-options curve. Silk Hand: every option works (fight, bribe, intimidate, 
  flee). Phantom Circuit: bribery weaker, they flee on you. Rust Collective: intimidation gone, fleeing pointless, negotiation       
  costly. Void Reavers: nothing but combat. Each step up the difficulty ladder is a step down the option ladder. That's elegant.     

  What's underexplored: The factions all have strong combat identities but their narrative identities are still thin in the docs. The
   generator is the right place to fix this — it's literally the tool for producing lore at scale. The faction-flavor guidance in §8 
  of discovery_generator.md already nudges this direction, but the doc could go further with a per-faction "voice and tone" guide for
   content writers (and for Claude). Want me to add that as a new section to the discovery_generator.md doc? It would slot naturally 
  into §3 (Reference Data → Factions) as an expanded subsection.